  {% set hasMultipleGroups = true %}
{% elif qa and qa.safeNames and qa.workableNames %}
  {% set hasMultipleGroups = true %}
{% endif %}

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

  <h3>
    {% if isWorkableOnly %}
      Which {{ cropDisplayName | lower }} varieties should I start with in {{ pageData.cityName }}?
    {% elif qa and qa.bestNames %}
      Why start with {{ qa.bestNames }}?
    {% else %}
      Which {{ cropDisplayName | lower }} varieties should I start with in {{ pageData.cityName }}?
    {% endif %}
  </h3>
  <p>
    {% if isWorkableOnly and qa.workableNames %}
      Start with {{ qa.workableNames }} because {% if workableIsPlural %}they are{% else %}it is{% endif %} the shortest realistic path for this crop in {{ pageData.cityName }}.
      {% if workableIsPlural %}
        Give them the warmest practical site you can, start them cleanly, and avoid slow early growth.
      {% elif qa.workableGrowingNotePhrase %}
        To improve the odds, {{ qa.workableGrowingNotePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        Good timing and steady early growth matter more than usual here.
      {% endif %}

    {% elif isBestOnly and qa.bestNames %}
      {% if qa.bestChoicePhrase %}
        Start with {{ qa.bestNames }} because {% if bestIsPlural %}they are{% else %}it is{% endif %} among the more realistic options for keeping this crop on track in {{ pageData.cityName }}.
        {% if bestIsPlural %}
          They help by shortening the path to harvest and reducing how much of the season has to go right before the crop starts producing.
        {% elif qa.bestTradeoffPhrase %}
          The tradeoff is that {{ qa.bestTradeoffPhrase }}.
        {% elif qa.bestGrowingNotePhrase %}
          For the best result, {{ qa.bestGrowingNotePhrase }}.
        {% endif %}
      {% else %}
        {% if bestIsPlural %}They are{% else %}It is{% endif %} the practical starting point because this crop needs the faster end of its range in {{ pageData.cityName }}.
      {% endif %}

    {% elif qa and qa.bestNames %}
      Start with {{ qa.bestNames }} because
      {% if qa.bestChoicePhrase %}
        {% if bestIsPlural %}they suit{% else %}it suits{% endif %} {{ qa.bestChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        {% if bestIsPlural %}they fit{% else %}it fits{% endif %} the main maturity range for {{ pageData.cityName }}.
      {% endif %}
      {% if bestIsPlural %}
        Use the variety notes to choose the specific trait you care about most.
      {% elif qa.bestGrowingNotePhrase %}
        For the best result, {{ qa.bestGrowingNotePhrase }}.
      {% elif qa.bestTradeoffPhrase %}
        The main tradeoff is that {{ qa.bestTradeoffPhrase }}.
      {% endif %}

    {% elif defaultVarietyDisplay %}
      Start with varieties in {{ defaultVarietyDisplay.rangePhrase }}. That is usually the strongest default maturity range for this crop in {{ pageData.cityName }}.

    {% else %}
      Start with varieties that leave dependable room in the local season rather than slower options that only work when everything goes right.
    {% endif %}
  </p>

  <h3>
    {% if hasMultipleGroups %}
      How should I choose between the groups on this page?
    {% else %}
      How should I choose between these varieties?
    {% endif %}
  </h3>
  <p>
    {% if isWorkableOnly %}
      Compare the variety notes, then focus on giving the crop the strongest start possible. With this crop in {{ pageData.cityName }}, the main risk is not choosing between many easy options; it is getting a short-season variety to finish well.

    {% elif qa and qa.safeNames and qa.workableNames %}
      First decide what you want the variety to do, then use the groups as a risk ladder.
      {% if qa.safeChoicePhrase %}
        The faster group is best when you want {{ qa.safeChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        The faster group is best when speed and margin matter most.
      {% endif %}
      {% if qa.bestChoicePhrase %}
        The main recommendation is the better starting point when you want {{ qa.bestChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        The main recommendation is the better starting point for the strongest normal fit.
      {% endif %}
      {% if qa.workableChoicePhrase %}
        The other varieties are worth a look when their specific strengths matter more than taking the safest route.
      {% else %}
        The other varieties are worth a look when a specific trait matters more than taking the safest route.
      {% endif %}

    {% elif qa and qa.safeNames %}
      First decide whether you want the main harvest type or the safer fast-end choice.
      {% if qa.bestChoicePhrase %}
        Use {{ qa.bestNames }} for {{ qa.bestChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        Use {{ qa.bestNames }} as the main recommendation.
      {% endif %}
      {% if qa.safeChoicePhrase %}
        Choose {{ qa.safeNames }} when you want {{ qa.safeChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        Choose {{ qa.safeNames }} when you want a faster harvest, more cushion, or a safer finish.
      {% endif %}

    {% elif qa and qa.workableNames %}
      First decide whether the main recommendation matches your goal.
      {% if qa.bestChoicePhrase %}
        Use {{ qa.bestNames }} for {{ qa.bestChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        Use {{ qa.bestNames }} as the cleanest local fit.
      {% endif %}
      {% if qa.workableChoicePhrase %}
        Look at {{ qa.workableNames }} when you want {{ qa.workableChoicePhrase }}.
      {% else %}
        Look at {{ qa.workableNames }} when the variety trait is more important than taking the safest path.
      {% endif %}

    {% elif isBestOnly and qa.bestNames %}
      Compare the variety notes.
      {% if bestIsPlural %}
        On pages like this, the decision is usually not whether the crop can handle a slower stretch option. It is which realistic early choice better matches your goal, whether that means the earliest harvest, a steadier short-season fit, or the specific harvest style you want most.
      {% elif qa.bestChoicePhrase %}
        The practical decision is whether {{ qa.bestChoicePhrase }} matches what you want from the crop.
      {% else %}
        The practical choice usually comes down to which realistic option best matches your goal.
      {% endif %}

    {% else %}
      Compare the variety notes first. When two choices look similar, lean toward the one with fewer days to maturity, a lower heat target, or a harvest type that better matches what you want.
    {% endif %}
  </p>

  {% if qa and qa.workableNames %}
    <h3>
      {% if isWorkableOnly %}
        {% if workableIsPlural %}Are{% else %}Is{% endif %} the workable {% if workableIsPlural %}options{% else %}option{% endif %} still worth growing?
      {% else %}
        {% if workableIsPlural %}Are{% else %}Is{% endif %} the other {% if workableIsPlural %}varieties{% else %}variety{% endif %} worth exploring?
      {% endif %}
    </h3>
    <p>
      {% if isWorkableOnly %}
        Yes, but treat {% if workableIsPlural %}them{% else %}it{% endif %} as careful short-season choices.
        {% if workableIsPlural %}
          Give them warm soil, a strong start, and as little delay as possible.
        {% elif qa.workableGrowingNotePhrase %}
          To make the attempt more realistic, {{ qa.workableGrowingNotePhrase }}.
        {% else %}
          {% if workableIsPlural %}They still need{% else %}It still needs{% endif %} good timing, steady early growth, and realistic expectations.
        {% endif %}

      {% else %}
        Yes{% if qa.workableChoicePhrase %}, especially if you want {{ qa.workableChoicePhrase }}{% endif %}.
        {% if workableIsPlural %}
          These are purpose-specific choices rather than backups, so use the variety notes to match the harvest style, root type, flavor, plant habit, or growing setup you actually want.
        {% elif qa.workableTradeoffPhrase %}
          The tradeoff is that {{ qa.workableTradeoffPhrase }}.
        {% elif qa.workableGrowingNotePhrase %}
          For the best result, {{ qa.workableGrowingNotePhrase }}.
        {% else %}
          {{ qa.workableNames }} can still make sense, but it usually needs better timing, steadier early growth, or more tolerance for risk than the main recommendation.
        {% endif %}
      {% endif %}
    </p>
  {% endif %}

  <h3>How much should days to maturity matter when choosing varieties?</h3>
  <p>
    Days to maturity are useful, but they are not the whole answer. A variety also needs enough local heat, a clean start, and enough room before the season gets tight. Use days to maturity as a first screen, then compare the variety's role on this page.
  </p>
</section>

